

Steps to Create EC2 Instance
Go to Amazon Web Services
In the search bar, type EC2 and select  Amazon EC2
Click on “Launch Instance”

Enter Name of your instance
Choose AMI (Amazon Machine Image)         //  Example: Amazon Linux, Ubuntu
Select Instance Type			 //   Example: t3.micro (Free tier eligible)
Create / Select Key Pair			//    Download .pem file safely

Allow ports:
SSH (22) → for login
HTTP (80) → for web server
HTTPS (443) → optional

Storage   // default is fine

Click “Launch Instance”
Wait for instance to start

 Verify
Go to Instances → Running Instances
Copy Public IP
Connect using:
SSH (Linux/Mac)
PuTTY (Windows)

ssh -i key.pem ec2-user@your-public-ip






















Create S3 Bucket
In search bar, type S3 and open
Amazon S3
Click on “Create bucket”

Enter Bucket Name		//Must be globally unique

Turn OFF only if you want public files (like website)

Click “Create bucket”

Upload Files
Open your bucket
Click “Upload”
Add files → Click Upload

Click uploaded file
Copy Object URL
If public access enabled → open in browser

To give permission to object 

Goto to bucket - click on permission - then Edit bucket policy - and paste below code with your bucket_name - and save 

{
    "Version": "2012-10-17",
    "Statement": [
        {
            "Sid": "PublicReadGetObject",
            "Effect": "Allow",
            "Principal": "*",
            "Action": "s3:GetObject",
            "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::YOUR-BUCKET-NAME/*"
        }
    ]
}












Steps to Create VPC (VPC and More)
In search bar, type VPC and open Amazon VPC
Click on “Create VPC”
Select “VPC and more” 

Enter Name Tag		// Example: my-auto-vpc
IPv4 CIDR Block		// Example: 10.0.0.0/16

Select:
Number of Availability Zones (e.g., 2)
Number of Public Subnets (e.g., 2)
Number of Private Subnets (e.g., 2)
AWS will automatically create subnets
Internet Gateway → Enabled (default)
NAT Gateway →
Select 1 per AZ (or none for free tier)
Click “Create VPC”

